# How to correctly migrate a collection's data? #6755 - GitHub
created: 2025-04-22, last updated: 2025-10-05, [Read more](https://github.com/pocketbase/pocketbase/discussions/6755)

let collection = app.findCollectionByNameOrId("common_categories");
const data = [
{
id: 'abc',
...
},
...
];
for (const type of data) {
let record = new Record(collection);
record.load(type);
app.save(record);
}
},
(db) => {
}
...
Unfortunately I don't think I can explain it better than what is already available in the documentation, but to simplify it, migrations are essentially **functions that execute only once in the running environment** and they could do almost anything - change the collection structure, adapt existing data to accommodate those changes, seed the database with predefined records, etc.
...
In that case, similar to a git conflict when multiple people edit the same code, it is up to the developers and their specific use case to decide how the conflict should be resolved.
In your particular situation I see 2 options:
- manually delete the conflicting records from the environment(s) before applying the new migration
- adapt your migration by checking before the records creation whether the predefined ids already exist and determine what to do in case such conflict occur (should the old record be deleted and the new one replace it or skip the new record and keep the existing one?)

